revision.text:
{{Infobox Muslim scholar | region = [[Saudi Arabia]] | era = Modern era | image = | caption = | name = Abdul-Rahman bin Nasir al-Barrak | birth_date = {{birth year and age|1933}} | death_date = | birth_place = Al Bukayriah, [[Al-Qassim Province]] | Maddhab = | school_tradition = | movement = [[Salafi]] | main_interests = | influences = | influenced = | notable_ideas = }}
'''Abdul-Rahman bin Nasir al-Barrak''' ({{lang-ar|عبد الرحمن بن ناصر البراك}}, born 1933 or 1934<ref>[http://albarrak.islamlight.net/index.php?option=content&task=view&id=1364&Itemid=45, "About Sheikh", Hijri calendar birthdate 1352] albarrak.islamlight.net</ref>) is a [[Saudi]] [[Salafi]] cleric.
In 1994, al-Barrak and other Saudi clerics were mentioned by name and praised by [[Osama bin Laden]] for opposing then-[[Grand Mufti of Saudi Arabia|Grand Mufti]] [[Abd al-Aziz ibn Baz]] in his [[s:Open Letter to Shaykh Bin Baz on the Invalidity of his Fatwa on Peace with the Jews|Open Letter to Shaykh Bin Baz on the Invalidity of his Fatwa on Peace with the Jews]].
His [[website]] was banned in Saudi Arabia because it was “promoting bold ideas and theses”.<ref>[http://www.csmonitor.com/World/Middle-East/2015/0602/Saudi-Arabia-presses-YouTube-imams-to-toe-the-line-on-Yemen Christian Science Monitor: "Saudi Arabia presses 'YouTube imams' to toe the line on Yemen - Popular Muslim clerics are using social media to stir dissent beyond the purview of government-controlled mosques and satellite TV stations. Saudi Arabia is sensitive to criticism of its war in Yemen" By Taylor Luck] June 2, 2015 |''Now Saudi authorities are cracking down on online dissent, blocking several popular sites – such as those of clerics such as Mohammed Munajjid and Abdulrahman Barrak – for “promoting bold ideas and thesis.”''</ref>
==Fatwas==
Al-Barrak has drawn attention for issuing controversial [[fatwa]]s, or religious edicts. One such fatwa called for strict [[gender segregation]].<ref>[http://in.reuters.com/article/worldNews/idINIndia-46408620100223?pageNumber=1&virtualBrandChannel=0&sp=true Saudi cleric backs gender segregation with fatwa], Reuters, 2010-02-23</ref> The fatwa states, "Whoever allows this mixing ... allows forbidden things, and whoever allows them is a [[kafir]] and this means defection from Islam ... Either he retracts or he must be killed ... because he disavows and does not observe the [[Sharia]]."
In March 2008, al-Barrak issued a fatwa that two writers for the newspaper ''[[Al Riyadh (newspaper)|Al Riyadh]]'', Abdullah bin Bejad al-Otaibi and Yousef Aba al-Khail, should be tried for [[apostasy]] for their "heretical articles" regarding the categorization of "unbelievers" and put to death if they did not repent.<ref>[https://www.reuters.com/article/idUSL15492468, Top Saudi cleric calls for writers' deaths] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304002631/https://www.reuters.com/article/idUSL15492468%2C |date=2016-03-04 }} Reuters, 2008-03-15</ref>
