{{About|the Estonian political party|raves without legal restrictions|Free party}} {{Infobox political party |country = Estonia |name = Estonian Free Party |native_name = Eesti Vabaerakond |logo = Estonian Free Party logo.png |logo_size = 250px | lang1 = Estonian | name_lang1 = Eesti Vabaerakond | colorcode = #0086CF | leader = [[Kaul Nurm]] | foundation = {{Start date|df=y|2014|9|20}} | ideology = [[Liberal conservatism]]<ref name="Nordsieck">{{Cite web|url=http://parties-and-elections.eu/estonia.html|title=Estonia|last=Nordsieck|first=Wolfram|date=2015|website=Parties and Elections in Europe}}</ref> | position = [[Centre-right politics|Centre-right]] | european = | europarl = | youth_wing = | international = | colours ={{Color box|#0086CF|border=darkgray}} Blue | membership_year = 2018 | membership = {{decrease}} 589<ref>{{cite web |url=https://ariregister.rik.ee/erakonnad.py |title=Äriregistri teabesüsteem |access-date=23 Nov 2018 |language=Estonian}}</ref> | headquarters = Koidu tn 23, [[Tallinn]] | website = {{URL|www.vabaerakond.ee}} | seats1_title = [[Riigikogu]] | seats1 = {{Composition bar|6|101|hex=#0086CF}} }}
The '''Estonian Free Party''' ({{lang-et|Eesti Vabaerakond}}) is an [[Estonia]]n [[Centre-right politics|centre-right]] political party founded in 2014.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-31681293|title=Estonia ruling party wins election|date=2015-03-02|work=BBC News|access-date=2018-10-25|language=en-GB}}</ref> The chairman of the party is [[Kaul Nurm]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Vabaerakond valis uueks esimeheks Kaul Nurme |url=https://www.err.ee/865342/fotod-vabaerakond-valis-uueks-esimeheks-kaul-nurme |language= Estonian |website=[[Eesti Rahvusringhääling|ERR]] |access-date=30 September 2018}}</ref> The party gained 8 seats after passing the 5-percent threshold in the [[Estonian parliamentary election, 2015|2015 Estonian parliamentary elections]].
==History== The [[nonprofit organization|nonprofit]] Estonian Free Party Founding Group was founded in January 2014. Originally it was to be founded by two organizations, [[Free Patriotic Citizen]] and [[Better Estonia]], but the latter decided to withdraw.<ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.delfi.ee/news/paevauudised/eesti/vik-ja-parem-eesti-asutavad-uue-erakonna-loomiseks-mtu?id=67666033 |title= VIK ja Parem Eesti asutavad uue erakonna loomiseks MTÜ |date= 23 January 2014 |publisher= [[Delfi (web portal)|Delfi]] |language= Estonian |access-date= 20 August 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url= http://uudised.err.ee/v/eesti/2f004fa6-0c0a-47f1-9dff-cee0f907bee9 |title= Ühenduste Vaba Isamaaline Kodanik ja Parem Eesti teed läksid lahku |date= 17 February 2014 |first=Merili |last=Nael |publisher= [[Eesti Rahvusringhääling]] |language= Estonian |access-date= 20 August 2015}}</ref>
Estonian Free Party was officially established on 20 September 2014, and [[Andres Herkel]] was elected as chairman.<ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.postimees.ee/2927133/vabaerakond-valis-esimeheks-andres-herkeli |title= Vabaerakond valis esimeheks Andres Herkeli |date= 20 September 2014 |publisher= [[Postimees]] |language= Estonian |access-date= 20 August 2015}}</ref> The party attracted numerous public figures, including former head of the [[Estonia Defence Forces|Defense Forces]] Admiral [[Tarmo Kõuts]], actor [[Ain Lutsepp]], and [[Jüri Adams]], a former government minister who was one of the main writers of the [[Constitution of Estonia]].<ref>{{cite news |url= http://news.err.ee/v/politics/ad3cd7e3-9244-48ce-986d-571c9894221a |title= Free Party Made Official |date= 8 October 2014 |publisher= [[Eesti Rahvusringhääling]] |access-date= 20 August 2015}}</ref>
During the [[Estonian parliamentary election, 2015|2015 Estonian parliamentary elections]], the Estonian Free Party received 49,883 votes, constituting 8.7 percent of the total, which garnered it 8 seats in the 101-member parliament.<ref>{{cite news |url= http://news.postimees.ee/3108019/reform-wins-estonia-s-parlt-elections-six-parties-secure-seats |title= Reform wins Estonia's parlt elections, six parties secure seats |date= 2 March 2015 |publisher= [[Postimees]] |access-date= 20 August 2015}}</ref> The Estonian Free Party's candidate for [[Prime Minister of Estonia|prime minister]], [[Artur Talvik]], who received the most votes of all the Estonian Free Party candidates, was not a member of the party himself.<ref>{{cite news |url= http://news.err.ee/v/politics/78db7ea2-ea01-48f1-a5ea-8864d25813bc |title= Rõivas most popular PM candidate |date= 23 February 2015 |first=Juhan-Markus |last=Laats |publisher= [[Eesti Rahvusringhääling]] |access-date= 22 August 2015}}</ref><ref name="soonvald">{{cite news |url= http://www.delfi.ee/news/riigikogu2015/videod/video-vabaerakonna-parteitu-esikoneleja-artur-talvik-meile-uritati-oosel-pai-teha-sest-arvatakse-et-oleme-lihtne-partner?id=70915651 |title= VIDEO: Vabaerakonna parteitu esikõneleja Artur Talvik: meile üritati öösel pai teha, sest arvatakse, et oleme lihtne partner |date= 2 March 2015 |first=Urmo |last=Soonvald |publisher= [[Delfi (web portal)|Delfi]] |language= Estonian |access-date= 22 August 2015}}</ref>
The Estonian Free Party participated in coalition talks together with the [[Estonian Reform Party]], [[Social Democratic Party (Estonia)|Social Democratic Party]], and [[Pro Patria and Res Publica Union]], but were left out of the coalition because their proposals to change the tax system were considered unacceptable. The Estonian Reform Party's unwillingness to reduce the state funding for political parties was cited as an issue by the Estonian Free Party.<ref name="tambur">{{cite news |url= http://news.err.ee/v/politics/9a422178-b0ea-461e-b208-7ead215b88cd |title= Coalition talks to continue between three parties, Free Party to go into opposition |date= 23 March 2015 |first=Silver |last=Tambur |publisher= [[Eesti Rahvusringhääling]] |access-date= 20 August 2015}}</ref>
==Political positions== Commentators have argued, that the Estonian Free Party lacks a clear ideology.<ref>{{cite news |url= http://epl.delfi.ee/news/eesti/on-keegi-nainud-vabaerakond-otsib-oma-maailmavaadet?id=72205049 |title= On keegi näinud? Vabaerakond otsib oma maailmavaadet |date= 14 August 2015 |first=Urmas |last=Jaagant |publisher= [[Eesti Päevaleht]] |language= Estonian |access-date= 22 August 2015}}</ref> It has been characterized as [[Centre-right politics|centre-right]], while chairman Andres Herkel described the party's ideology as right-wing liberal.<ref>{{cite news |url= http://news.err.ee/v/main_news/4249bcba-7176-4b74-af11-9e4812c78368 |title= Ruling Reform Party wins Estonian election, fending off challenge from archrival Center |date= 1 March 2014 |first=Kristopher |last=Rikken |publisher= [[Eesti Rahvusringhääling]] |access-date= 22 August 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url= http://uudised.err.ee/v/eesti/49f614aa-a675-4dc5-a26a-cf5f3a46d5a4 |title= Vabaerakond lubab riigi rahvale tagasi tuua |date= 20 September 2014 |first=Heikki |last=Aasaru |publisher= [[Eesti Rahvusringhääling]] |language= Estonian |access-date= 22 August 2015}}</ref>
The party advocates raising the personal [[income tax]], while on the other hand also raising the non-taxable basic exemption to support the poorer majority of taxpayers. The party's program also includes increased taxes on alcohol, tobacco, and confectionery. In economic policy, the party supports a relatively liberal approach, especially to support small businesses.<ref>{{cite news |url= http://uudised.err.ee/v/eesti/eab2aebb-cccd-4e68-94a4-f000035e8b03 |title= Galerii: Vabaerakond kinnitas valimisprogrammi ja nimekirjad |date= 11 January 2015 |first=Allan |last=Rajavee |publisher= [[Eesti Rahvusringhääling]] |language= Estonian |access-date= 22 August 2015}}</ref> The party has advocated reduction of state funding of political parties.<ref name="tambur"/>
The Estonian Free Party has declared its opposition to the [[Recognition of same-sex unions in Estonia|law recognising same-sex unions in Estonia]], claiming that in its current form the law does not solve any problems. The party claims that the law needs to be revised and possibly also split into multiple, separate laws.<ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.delfi.ee/news/paevauudised/eesti/eesti-vabaerakond-kujundas-kooseluseaduse-suhtes-oma-seisukoha?id=70635653 |title= Eesti Vabaerakond kujundas kooseluseaduse suhtes oma seisukoha |date= 24 January 2015 |publisher= [[Delfi (web portal)|Delfi]] |language= Estonian |access-date= 22 August 2015}}</ref> The party opposes compulsory [[European Union|EU]]-wide migrant quotas in regard to [[European migrant crisis]], and insists that the number of refugees to be accepted needs to be determined through negotiations.<ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.delfi.ee/news/paevauudised/eesti/vabaerakonna-avaldus-pagulaste-teemal-saabuvad-pogenikud-tuleb-uhiskonda-integreerida-ja-selle-tarvis-tuleb-raha-juurde-kusida?id=71676713 |title= Vabaerakonna avaldus pagulaste teemal: saabuvad põgenikud tuleb ühiskonda integreerida ja selle tarvis tuleb raha juurde küsida |date= 10 June 2015 |publisher= [[Delfi (web portal)|Delfi]] |language= Estonian |access-date= 22 August 2015}}</ref>
