{{Use mdy dates|date=June 2013}} {{infobox Museum |name= Gulf Coast Archive and Museum of GLBT History, Inc. |website= {{url|http://gcam.org/}} |location= 401 Branard, [[Houston]], Texas, USA |chairperson= Craig Farrell |curator= Judy Reeves |established= July 1999 |logo= GulfCoastArchiveAndMuseumLogo.jpg |coordinates = {{coord|29.737095|-95.384532|display=inline}} }} The '''Gulf Coast Archive and Museum of Gay, Lesbian, Bisexual and Transgender History, Inc. (GCAM)''' is an [[LGBT history]] organization located in [[Neartown, Houston]], Texas (United States). <ref name=formed>{{Cite news |author=Gray, Lisa |title=Out of the Closets |url=http://www.houstonpress.com/2000-08-03/news/out-of-the-closets/ |newspaper=[[Houston Press]] |publisher=Folb, Stuart |location=Houston, TX |date=August 3, 2000 |accessdate=September 15, 2009}} </ref>
GCAM was created to collect, preserve and provide access to historical items from the [[LGBT community]] of the [[Gulf Coast of the United States|Gulf Coast]] area of Texas.<ref name=main>{{Cite web | title = Mission Statement | publisher = Gulf Coast Archive and Museum of GLBT History, Inc. | url = http://gcam.org | accessdate = September 15, 2009}} </ref> The archive encourages education of and research by anyone interested in learning about any aspects of the LGBT community. The organization sponsors meetings for the dissemination of information and display of collected materials.
==History== GCAM began meeting in July 1999 and officially incorporated in May 2000. The initial opening of the museum doors occurred Friday, June 16, 2000, in a small shared warehouse space on Capitol Street. <ref name=formed/> <ref name=creation>{{Cite news|title=Our History is Worth Preserving |author=Unknown |url=http://www.outsmartmagazine.com/issue/i06-00/in.html |periodical=OutSmart Magazine |publisher=Greg Jeu |location=Houston, TX |date=June 2000 |accessdate=September 16, 2009 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081005033732/http://www.outsmartmagazine.com/issue/i06-00/in.html |archivedate=October 5, 2008 }}</ref> By June 2001, the museum had moved into an apartment on West Main Street. <ref name=wmain>{{Cite news|title=GCAM Time Capsule |author=Unknown |url=http://www.outsmartmagazine.com/issue/i06-01/guide.html |periodical=OutSmart Magazine |publisher=Greg Jeu |location=Houston, TX |date=June 2001 |accessdate=September 16, 2009 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090212005754/http://outsmartmagazine.com/issue/i06-01/guide.html |archivedate=February 12, 2009 }} </ref> In May 2005, GCAM officially closed its museum to focus on preserving the history of the community. <ref name=closed>{{Cite news|title=GCAM Makes Historic Moves |author=Unknown |url=http://www.outsmartmagazine.com/cms-this_issue/200505--History%2C+Pride%2C+and+Rock+%27n%27+Roll.html#gcam |periodical=OutSmart Magazine |publisher=Greg Jeu |location=Houston, TX |date=May 2005 |accessdate=September 16, 2009 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081005033727/http://www.outsmartmagazine.com/cms-this_issue/200505--History%2C+Pride%2C+and+Rock+%27n%27+Roll.html |archivedate=October 5, 2008 }} </ref> Later, GCAM moved into an office at the Montrose Center with an ongoing exhibit space there on the public walls of the space. <ref name=crown>{{Cite news | title = The Million-Dollar Crown | author = Wolf, Brandon | url = http://www.hmh.org/ViewExhibits.aspx?ID=57&ExhibitType=Past | periodical = OutSmart Magazine | publisher = Greg Jeu | location = Houston, TX | date = May 2009 | accessdate = September 16, 2009 }} </ref>
==Exhibits== June through September 2004, GCAM was proud to be able to assist the Holocaust Museum Houston to present Nazi Persecution of Homosexuals 1933–1945. <ref name=nazi>{{Cite web | title = Nazi Persecution of Homosexuals 1933–1945 | publisher = Holocaust Museum Houston | url = http://www.hmh.org/ex_show.asp?id=19 | accessdate = September 15, 2009}} </ref>
