{{Orphan|date=March 2018}}
{{Notability|date=April 2018}}

[[File:Ely Cathedral Exterior, Cambridgeshire, UK - Diliff.jpg|thumb|right|Ely Cathedral Exterior, Cambridgeshire]]The '''Lands and Liberties of the Church at Ely''' was a 1080 court case and an appeal, where the [[Abbott of Ely]] sought recovery of lands that had been taken at [[Norman Conquest|the Conquest]],<ref>Liber Eliensis 251; Publisher: Anglican Christian Society https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=mdp.35112203930609;view=1up;seq=93 p22].</ref> 14 years beforehand.

The liberty of [[Ely, Cambridgeshire|Ely]] was established in (King) Edgar's charters for the refounded monastery in 970. Edward the Confessor reiterated the liberties in 1052 and then William the Conqueror restated them.<ref>E. Miller, 'The Ely Land Pleas in the reign of William I', E.H.R. lxii (1947), 455.</ref>

Wherever the church of Ely had lands, it had its own courts where defendants in cases of theft could vouch to warranty. Severing of a hand and death were among the common penalties for significant theft.<ref>Trinity College. Camb. O. 2. 1, f. 115a.</ref>

The court case can be viewed as a part of a large collection of [[pleading]]s against a process of [[Norman conquest of England#Elite replacement|Norman]]ization that within a [[decade]] saw 64[[percent|%]] of land in [[England]] consolidated into the hands of just 150 individuals, and many of the [[nobility]] and churches deprived of their estates.

